<subSubSection id="92F965007C21FF98FF595969FD31FB9E" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="description">
<paragraph id="DA5C368B7C21FF98FF595969FD92FD36" blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FF595969FEFAFE11" bold="true" box="[151,297,361,387]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Description.</emphasis>
Body narrowly elongate. Head short with obliquely inclined mouthparts, broadest at across the eyes; frons steep and narrow, with a vague median ridge reaching vertex; genae very short; postvertex of male protruding backward to form a short horn in lateral view (
<figureCitation id="42D82A0E7C21FF98FD6F59B2FD21FE5E" box="[673,754,434,460]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1140,1752]" captionTargetId="figure-44@4.[151,1436,1128,1764]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Head and pronotum of Unicornileptura spp. 8–11, U. emeiensis sp. nov.; 12,13, U. laticollis sp. nov. 8, 9, head in lateral view (a) and frontal view (b); 10–13, pronotum in dorsal view. 8, 10, 12, male; 9, 11, 13, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6487983" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6487983/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Fig. 8a</figureCitation>
), triangular shaped in frontal view (
<figureCitation id="42D82A0E7C21FF98FB4D59B2FB06FE5F" box="[1155,1237,434,461]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1140,1752]" captionTargetId="figure-44@4.[151,1436,1128,1764]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Head and pronotum of Unicornileptura spp. 8–11, U. emeiensis sp. nov.; 12,13, U. laticollis sp. nov. 8, 9, head in lateral view (a) and frontal view (b); 10–13, pronotum in dorsal view. 8, 10, 12, male; 9, 11, 13, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6487983" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6487983/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Fig. 8b</figureCitation>
), almost reaching anterior margin of pronotum; temples moderately developed, shorter than longitudinal eye diameter, roundly constricted to neck. Eyes almost entire, finely facetted; interocular space wider than distance between antennal cavities. Maxillary palpus with fusiform terminal segment, about 1.5 times as long as the penultimate segment. Antennae inserted near anterior margin of eyes, reaching or exceeding elytral midlength; scape clavate, abruptly bent down near apex; flagellum filiform with apices of basal 5 flagellomeres slightly thickened, first flagellomere longer than second, shorter than third.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DA5C368B7C21FF98FF095AAEFD90FCCA" blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Pronotum trapezoid, nearly as broad as head; sides weakly rounded with obtusely angulate or broadly rounded apical corner and short acute hind angles; hind angles short and acute; disk gently convex. Prosternum without transverse excavation between procoxae and anterior margin; procoxal cavities widely opened posteriorly; prosternal process very narrow with slightly dilated apex. Mesosternal process gradually declivous anteriorly in lateral view. Mesocoxal cavity open to episternum.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DA5C368B7C21FF98FF095B62FD31FB9E" blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Elytra elongate, more than 3 times as long as humeral width, more than 2.5 times as long as head and pronotum combined; slightly narrowed apically in male, subparallel sided in female, then roundly narrowed to apices; disk metallic green or blue. Abdomen completely covered by elytra; abdominal ventrites I about 1.5 times as long as II to V respectively. Legs moderately long and slender; femora weakly clavate; hind tarsi with first tarsomere slightly longer than the following two tarsomeres combined.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="92F965007C21FF98FF095C16FDEAFBC6" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="DA5C368B7C21FF98FF095C16FDEAFBC6" blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FF095C16FE9DFBA2" bold="true" box="[199,334,1046,1072]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the combination of Latin ūnicornis, meaning one-horned and leptura, the name of the 
<typeStatus id="055888297C21FF98FAA25C16FA4FFBA2" box="[1388,1436,1046,1072]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">type</typeStatus>
genus of 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FF305C3AFEB9FBC6" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[254,362,1082,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lepturini">Lepturini</taxonomicName>
. Gender feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="92F965007C21FF98FF095C5DFDBDFBEA" box="[199,622,1117,1144]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="DA5C368B7C21FF98FF095C5DFDBDFBEA" blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" box="[199,622,1117,1144]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FF095C5DFEB2FBE5" bold="true" box="[199,353,1117,1143]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="A2F4761B7C21FF98FEA95C5EFE7DFBEA" box="[359,430,1118,1144]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">China</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion id="1827F8697C21FF98FE775C5EFDC4FBEA" box="[441,535,1118,1144]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
; 
<collectingRegion id="1827F8697C21FF98FDEC5C5EFDB9FBEA" box="[546,618,1118,1144]" country="China" name="Hubei" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Hubei</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="92F965007C21FF98FF095C82FE8FF92A" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="DA5C368B7C21FF98FF095C82FBDCFAE6" blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FF095C82FEE7FB0E" bold="true" box="[199,308,1154,1180]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Remarks</emphasis>
. This new genus should be placed into 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FCC15C82FCA4FB0E" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[783,887,1154,1180]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lepturini">Lepturini</taxonomicName>
by the feature of prothorax without transverse groove or depression in front of coxal cavities (
<bibRefCitation id="BE724B7A7C21FF98FD6E5CA6FC93FB53" author="Gressitt, J. L." box="[672,832,1190,1217]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3244" refString="Gressitt, J. L. (1951) Longicorn beetles of China. In: Lepesme, P. (Ed.). Longicornia, etudes et notes sur les longicornes. Vol. 2. Paul Lechevalier, Paris, pp. 1 - 667, 22 pls." type="journal volume" year="1951">Gressitt, 1951</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="BE724B7A7C21FF98FC845CA6FC37FB52" author="Villiers, A." box="[842,996,1190,1216]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3440" refString="Villiers, A. (1978) Faune des Coleopteres de France, I. Cerambycidae. Encyclopedie Entomologique 42. Paul Lechevallier, Paris, xxviii + 611 pp, 1802 figs." type="book" year="1978">Villiers, 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="BE724B7A7C21FF98FC205CA6FB10FB52" author="Tsherepanov, A. I." box="[1006,1219,1190,1216]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3400" refString="Tsherepanov, A. I. (1990) Cerambycidae of Northern Asia, volume 1. Prioninae, Disteniinae, Lepturinae, Aseminae. Oxonian Press, New Delhi, xvi + 642 pp., 296 figs." type="book" year="1990">Tsherepanov, 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="BE724B7A7C21FF98FB035CA6FA89FB53" author="Bense, U." box="[1229,1370,1190,1217]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3212" refString="Bense, U. (1995) Longicorn Beetles. Illustrated Key to the Cerambycidae and Vesperidae of Europe. Margraf Verlag, Weikersheim, 512 pp., 1260 figs." type="book" year="1995">Bense, 1995</bibRefCitation>
; etc.). It superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FE765CCAFC8EFB77" authority="Audinet-Serville, 1835" authorityName="Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1835" box="[440,861,1226,1253]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Grammoptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FE765CCAFD84FB76" box="[440,599,1226,1252]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Grammoptera</emphasis>
Audinet-Serville, 1835
</taxonomicName>
especially the group of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FACF5CCAFA4EFB76" authorityName="Matsushita &amp; Tamanuki" authorityYear="1940" box="[1281,1437,1226,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Neoencyclops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FACF5CCAFA4EFB76" box="[1281,1437,1226,1252]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Neoencyclops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
regarding their overall habitus e.g. slender body, metallic colored elytra and similar proportion of body, but it can be readily distinguished from the latter by the curved scape, transverse pronotum and extremely elongate elytra. And fundamentally, it is rather unique among the Asia lepturine genera by its head significantly sexually dimorphic, provided with a cranial horn in male (
<figureCitation id="42D82A0E7C21FF98FDF05D5AFD5DFAE6" box="[574,654,1370,1396]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1140,1752]" captionTargetId="figure-44@4.[151,1436,1128,1764]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Head and pronotum of Unicornileptura spp. 8–11, U. emeiensis sp. nov.; 12,13, U. laticollis sp. nov. 8, 9, head in lateral view (a) and frontal view (b); 10–13, pronotum in dorsal view. 8, 10, 12, male; 9, 11, 13, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6487983" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6487983/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Fig. 8a</figureCitation>
) which absent in female (
<figureCitation id="42D82A0E7C21FF98FC615D5AFBD2FAE6" box="[943,1025,1370,1396]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1140,1752]" captionTargetId="figure-44@4.[151,1436,1128,1764]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Head and pronotum of Unicornileptura spp. 8–11, U. emeiensis sp. nov.; 12,13, U. laticollis sp. nov. 8, 9, head in lateral view (a) and frontal view (b); 10–13, pronotum in dorsal view. 8, 10, 12, male; 9, 11, 13, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6487983" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6487983/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Fig. 9a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DA5C368B7C21FF98FF095D7EFE8FF92A" blockId="1.[151,1437,361,1720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
The presence of horn-shaped projection of head mostly found in male was rarely reported from worldwide 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FF595DA2FEEAFA2E" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[151,313,1442,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cerambycidae</taxonomicName>
and currently limited to some lamiine tribe which originated from different portions, e.g. single postclypeal horn in 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FEB45DC7FE0AFA72" authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1867" box="[378,473,1479,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Momisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FEB45DC7FE0AFA72" box="[378,473,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Momisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Astathini or paired in 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FD325DC7FC8FFA72" authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[764,860,1479,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Mauesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FD325DC7FC8FFA72" box="[764,860,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Mauesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Mauesiini; mandibular horns in 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FB3D5DC6FA4EFA72" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1938" box="[1267,1437,1478,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Chariesthoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FB3D5DC6FA4EFA72" box="[1267,1437,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Chariesthoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Tragocephalini; antennal tubercular horns in some taxon of 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FCAE5DEAFAF2F996" authority="(Svacha &amp; Lawrence, 2014)" baseAuthorityName="Svacha &amp; Lawrence" baseAuthorityYear="2014" box="[864,1313,1514,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Onciderini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Onciderini (
<bibRefCitation id="BE724B7A7C21FF98FC265DEBFACAF996" author="Svacha, P. &amp; Lawrence, J. F." box="[1000,1305,1514,1542]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" pagination="1868" refId="ref3296" refString="Svacha, P. &amp; Lawrence, J. F. (2014) Vesperidae Mulsant, 1839; Oxypeltidae Lacordaire, 1868; Disteniidae J. Thomson, 1861; Cerambycidae Latreille, 1802. In: Leschen R. A. B. &amp; Beutel, R. G. (Eds.), Handbook of Zoology, Arthropoda: Insecta; Coleoptera, Beetles. Vol. 3. Morphology and systematics (Phytophaga). Walter de Gruyter, Berlin / Boston, pp. 16 - 177. https: // doi. org / 10.1515 / 9783110274462.16" type="book chapter" year="2014">Švácha &amp; Lawrence, 2014</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and also a postclypeal horn in Afirican genus 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FDE65E0FFD6BF9BA" box="[552,696,1551,1576]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Prosopocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FDE65E0FFD6BF9BA" box="[552,696,1551,1576]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Prosopocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FD2E5E0EFB58F9BB" authority="(Adlbauer et al., 2015)" baseAuthorityName="Adlbauer" baseAuthorityYear="2015" box="[736,1163,1550,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Prosopocerini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Prosopocerini (
<bibRefCitation id="BE724B7A7C21FF98FC455E0EFB57F9BB" author="Adlbauer, K. &amp; Beck, R." box="[907,1156,1550,1577]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" refId="ref3175" refString="Adlbauer, K. &amp; Beck, R. (2015) Katalog und Fotoatlas der Bockkafer Athiopiens (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Taita Publishers, Hradec Kralove, 312 pp., 912 figs." type="book" year="2015">
Adlbauer 
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FC305E0FFBE3F9BA" box="[1022,1072,1550,1576]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">et al</emphasis>
., 2015
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The cranial specialized horn found in 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FEF65E32FE3DF9DE" authority="Bi &amp; Chen &amp; Ohbayashi, 2022" authorityName="Bi &amp; Chen &amp; Ohbayashi" authorityYear="2022" box="[312,494,1586,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Unicornileptura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FEF65E32FE3DF9DE" box="[312,494,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">Unicornileptura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="E897EA997C21FF98FE385E32FD8CF9DE" bold="true" box="[502,607,1586,1612]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F3A457E27C21FF98FE385E32FD8CF9DE" box="[502,607,1586,1612]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
probably the first discover of such structure in 
<taxonomicName id="1DE34D087C21FF98FBB85E32FB21F9DE" box="[1142,1266,1586,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lepturinae">Lepturinae</taxonomicName>
, or even firstly reported from the whole group of longicorn beetles. Unfortunately such unique feature was recognized later in the laboratory based on dry specimens, its biological or ecological significance remains uncertain and requires further field observation.
</paragraph>
